Design decision for the APP
    --> There are three types of classes : MainController, ComponentController, Component
    --> There is exactly one MainController for entire app.
    --> MainController  is brain (decides flow). workflow coordinator
    --> ComponentController controlles exactly one component
    --> Component renders UI widgets. dumb renderer only

Final clean principle : 
    --> MainController defines the event flow. 
    --> ComponentControllers execute their part of that flow.
    --> Component controllers provide small UI actions that MainController can combine as needed.

MainController
    --> All coordination happens through MainController only.
    --> Only MainController should access the global store.
    --> each event has one entry method in MainController called eventHandlers
    --> event handler methods may call : zero, one, or multiple methods of ComponentController
    --> for each event it calls the relevant component controllers in sequence
    --> ideally no of methods shoud be one more than the no of events that occur in App lifecycle.
    --> There shoud be a seprate method for initializing the app.
    --> MainController decides the order and conditional branching
    --> One event may map to several UI actions in the same component controller
    --> It is the orchestrator.
    --> It call services, perform API calls, compute domain logic, decide workflows


The component :
    --> is a dumb renderer
    --> Create and own UI widgets (labels, buttons, inputs, layouts).
    --> Expose setters to update UI elements.
    --> Expose getters to access widget state if needed.
    --> Emit signals/events for user interactions.
    --> Organize its child widgets using a separate layout method.
    --> It should only display/hide/modify child widgets and emit user actions.
    --> It should not contain business logic or decision-making.
    --> shoud not take decisions as to what to display.
    --> shoud not decide how to format data
    --> Should NOT hardcode default text (labels, placeholders, warnings)

The component_controller :
    --> manages only one component.
    --> acts as a UI adapter between MainController and the component.
    --> It should call setters on the component to update UI.
    --> It should never directly manipulate layout structure.
    --> It should not hardcode business assumptions — only reflect what is passed from MainController.
    --> It does not contain business logic.
    --> It does not access or mutate global state directly (state is owned by MainController)
    --> controlls widget text, visibility, enabled/disabled states
    --> It should be reusable with its component. 
    --> It should not depend on other components, controllers and application-wide logic.
    --> Must NOT: call services, perform API calls, compute domain logic, decide workflows.
    --> A ComponentController must never call another ComponentController.
    --> It does not subscribe to store directly.
    --> It only reacts when MainController calls its methods.

Only create a method in a ComponentController if that component is affected by that event. Also very important, some times it is difficult to have just one method in component_controller for a certain event because main_controller takes some decisions in between. So in such cases ther can be multiple methods in component_conrollers for such event handling.
    
UI State Modeling. 
    --> Instead of scattered updates, prefer state-based methods:
    --> render_empty_state(...)
    --> render_loading_state(...)
    --> render_loaded_state(...)
    --> render_error_state(...)
    --> This keeps UI predictable and easy to debug.

